<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="43" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,664,1348]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,324,896,922]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is characterized by the forewing having two white basal lines and a rounded spot at costal 
<number box="[259,272,936,962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[281,296,936,962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" value="4.0">4</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[314,388,936,962]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="4.[151,275,1408,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,426,1383]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,426,1384]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Adults of Promalactis spp. 7, P. apicispinifera sp. nov.; 8, P. infulata Wang, Li et Zheng; 9, P. semantris (Meyrick); 10, P. densidentalis Wang et Li." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275206/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[371,388,936,962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). It is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[588,738,936,961]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Promalactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suzukiella">
<emphasis box="[588,738,936,961]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">P. suzukiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
both superficially and internally, but can be distinguished from it by male with the uncus having a pair of slender posterolateral processes, the costa extending to a small apex-setose process and the juxta bearing one larger spine and two small teeth posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[1243,1332,1013,1039]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[183,1419,212,1563]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,194,1567]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20. Male genitalia Promalactis spp. 17, P. apicispinifera sp. nov.; 18, P. infulata Wang, Li et Zheng; 19, P. semantris (Meyrick); 20, P. densidentalis Wang et Li." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275208/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[1299,1332,1013,1039]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
); and by female with the lamella postvaginalis being a pair of more or less sclerotized triangular plates (
<figureCitation box="[1273,1361,1052,1078]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 26" captionStartId="9.[151,272,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[192,1379,194,1927]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,194,1955]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 26. Female genitalia Promalactis spp. 21, P. quinilineata sp. nov.; 22, P. longiuncata sp. nov.; 23, P. biovata sp. nov.; 24, P. lobatifera sp. nov.; 25, P. apicispinifera sp. nov.; 26, P. semantris (Meyrick)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275209/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[1328,1361,1052,1078]" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Promalactis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suzukiella">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="43">P. suzukiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the uncus is broad at base and narrowed to pointed apex, the costa extends to a fingerlike process with fine hairs and the juxta lacks the large spine and small teeth posteriorly in males; and the lamella postvaginalis in females is somewhat a rectangular plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
